'''Cablegami''' is a technique used in the building of computer cases that involves the routing of various computer cables behind components such as [[motherboards]]. This is done to minimise the amount of cable visible from the outside of the case, for asthetic appeal especially in cases with a windowed side. It is also done to remove obstructions from airflow within a case for the purpose of lowering temperatures by increasing airflow or to reduce noise created by the turbulence the cables create.